name: Stuffed Cabbage With Lemony Rice and Sumac

steps.instruction:
Made by Andy Baraghani and can be found [here](https://www.bonappetit.com/recipe/stuffed-cabbage-with-lemony-rice-and-sumac)

### Prep
- Rinse the rice
- Finely chop the onion
- Chop the tender herbs
- Chop the raisins 

### Steps
1. Line a baking sheet with a clean kitchen towel or a few layers of paper towels; set aside
2.  Working in batches, cook cabbage leaves in a large pot of boiling generously salted water until bright green and pliable, about 2 minutes per batch
3. Transfer leaves to a bowl of ice water to cool; reserve pot of water for cooking rice. Transfer cabbage leaves to prepared baking sheet and let drain
4. Return water in pot to a boil and cook rice, stirring often, until grains swell and rise to the surface, 36 minutes (depending on quality of rice). Bite into a few grains to test; they should be al dente (rice will finish cooking when baked inside the cabbage)
5. Drain rice and rinse under cold running water to stop it from cooking further. Drain again and transfer to a large bowl.
6. Wipe out pot. Pour in  cup oil and set pot over medium heat. 
7. Add onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until softened and golden, 79 minutes
8. Add pine nuts and cook, stirring often, until nuts smell toasty and have slightly darkened in color and onion is almost jammy, about 5 minutes
9. Mix in herbs, raisins, and 2 Tbsp. sumac and cook, still stirring, until herbs have slightly darkened in color and are very fragrant, about 2 minutes
10. Remove from heat and stir in lemon juice; let cool 5 minutes.
11. Add onion mixture and egg to rice and mix well; season generously with salt and pepper
12. Wipe out pot; reserve
13. Working with 1 cabbage leaf at a time, cut out the thickest part of rib by making a thin V-shape; discard
14. Place 3 heaping Tbsp. filling in the center, running crosswise across leaf
15. Starting at the base where you cut the V, fold notched side of leaf up and over filling, then fold in sides and roll up leaf like a burrito
16. Arrange cabbage rolls, seam side down, in a single layer in reserved pot
17. Add butter and  cup water and bring to a simmer over medium-high heat
18. Reduce heat to low, cover pot, and steam rolls until filling is cooked through and leaves are tender, 1825 minutes
19. Divide cabbage rolls among plates; drizzle with oil and sprinkle with sumac and pepper. Serve with sour cream

ingredients.note: Such as Parsley, Mint, Dill, and or Tarragon
Sumac, a tart, citrusy spice generally sold in ground form, can be found at Middle Eastern markets, specialty foods stores, and online.
